ğŸ¯ Model Selection in Coding Agent Context
Key Insight: Users are ALREADY in a Claude session!
Current Session Model:
User opens Claude Code â†’ Chooses model (Opus/Sonnet/Haiku)
  â†“
That model handles ALL interactions by default
  â†“
Skills/agents CAN specify different models
  â†“
But adds latency (model switching)
Revised Model Strategy:
Option A: Use User's Current Model (Simplest)
# In all agents - NO model specified

---
name: prompt-enhancer
# model: <not specified - uses session model>
tools: file_read, file_create, str_replace
---

Adapt behavior based on detected model:
- If Opus: Full creative enhancement
- If Sonnet: Targeted enhancements (works great!)
- If Haiku: Template-based substitution only
Pros:
âœ… No model switching overhead
âœ… Works with whatever user has access to
âœ… Respects user's cost/speed preferences
âœ… Simpler architecture
Cons:
âš ï¸ Quality varies by user's model choice
âš ï¸ Haiku might struggle with complex enhancements
Option B: Recommend Model in Docs
# In README.md

## Model Recommendations

PromptForge works with any Claude model, but:

**Sonnet 4.5** (recommended)
- Best balance of speed and quality
- Handles 95% of enhancements excellently
- Fast enough for real-time iteration

**Opus 4.5** (if you want best quality)
- Highest quality enhancements
- Better at complex customizations
- Slower and more expensive

**Haiku 4.5** (for browsing only)
- Great for /prompt-browse and /prompt-score
- Enhancement quality limited
- Recommend upgrading to Sonnet for customization
Option C: Agent-Specific Model Override (Advanced)
# In plugin.json

{
  "agents": [
    {
      "name": "prompt-enhancer",
      "preferredModel": "sonnet",
      "fallbackToSessionModel": true
    },
    {
      "name": "prompt-researcher",
      "preferredModel": "haiku",
      "fallbackToSessionModel": true
    }
  ]
}
Behavior:
If user has Sonnet/Opus â†’ Uses their model
If user has Haiku â†’ Agent suggests "upgrade to Sonnet for better results"
User can override in settings
